Drunk on corruption
My friend Boris was about to leave my place, drunk.
I therefore suggested he not drive.
He asked me why.
"You've been drinking," I said to him, "don't you fear the police?"
Boris replied to me: "No, I have a document with Benjamin Franklin's likeness, it always comes in handy."
He showed me his driver's license with a 100-dollar bill slipped next to it.
Of course, I knew that the police take bribes, but I was worried that Boris would meet a cop who wasn't corrupt.
"Impossible," declared Boris, "to enter the traffic police department, you have to buy your chief's silence."
If you don't take bribes, how can you buy your chief's silence?
Half of the drivers in Moscow use illegally purchased driver's licenses.
The fools who try to do things the right way drown in bureaucratic red tape.
By paying 100 dollars, you can drive around town without brakes!"
Corruption and embezzlement have always existed in Russia, before Lenin's October Revolution and after.
But never at the record levels we see today.
Everyone accepts bribes, everywhere and for anything.
According to Boris, the only ones who don't accept them are those to whom none are offered.
Corruption thrives in most institutions, and the fight against corruption always ends in a disaster or abandonment.
The police, prosecutors, customs officials, and even the Kremlin: no one anywhere is immune.
Recently, I was visiting a dacha village in one of Moscow's most beautiful suburbs.
It was a luxurious place but similar to the gulag with its high-security fences and guards.
Examining the pretentious and tastelessly decorated houses, I asked who owned them and was told that one belonged to a Moscow deputy mayor, another to a famous singer, and another to the son of Moscow's prosecutor.
But the most attractive property belonged to a modest official from the tax service.
Corruption now represents a greater threat to Russia than the Chechen war.
In fact, the Chechen war would not have lasted as long if it had not been conducted by corrupt generals, officers, officials, and police who sell weapons and supplies to the rebels.
Russian television recently showed a bus shuttling between Grozny and Moscow, the same bus that brought 120 kilograms of explosives to Moscow used in the Dubrovka theater siege, where so many victims perished during the assault aimed at freeing the hostages.
A passenger on the bus covered the explosives with a cloth soaked in acid to prevent the customs dogs from smelling them.
A well-meaning but useless precaution.
No one controls the buses anymore.
The driver, who didn't know what he was transporting, said he was stopped 50 times along his route, and always for the same thing.
A police officer would come to him and ask, "do you know what the price is?" and the driver would reply, "of course, I know it," paying the bribe before leaving.
Without a bribe, the bus would have been delayed for hours at every stop, amounting to days for the entire journey.
The war against Chechnya continues endlessly not only because Chechen rebels have allies in Al Qaeda and the entire "international terrorist" network but also because Russian corruption is their ally.
The police, the army, civilians who accept bribes, and thieves, who first tax Chechen civilians or simply steal their belongings, sell weapons and explosives to terrorists, provide maps indicating where the minefields are, and supply the rebels with forged documents.
In May of this year, during the explosions in Kaspiisk, the terrorists used weapons purchased from Russian army officers.
The rebels have modern weapons.
Where do they come from?
In the mountains where the rebels hide there are no gun shops.
But the 80,000 Russian soldiers fighting the rebels have, on the other hand, supplies of ammunition, from which the weapons are stolen and sold.
And not just weapons: some young officers sell their own men into slavery.
Russian corruption has reached catastrophic levels, and yet no fight has been launched against this plague.
Punish corruption more severely?
This would only increase the cost of corruption.
The harsher the punishment, the more you will have to pay to avoid it.
No official wants to fight corruption because they themselves are corrupt.
Thus, those called "the simple people" view this phenomenon with goodwill.
They say of their mayor, "Of course he steals, but look at all he has done for the city!"
Ordinary people also do not like honest workers.
Why?
A train ticket costs 100 rubles, but by paying a small bribe, one can travel for 50 rubles.
Both the traveler and the conductor benefit from this system.
An honest old grandmother once told me that she had bought a ticket and tried to board the train.
The conductor had stopped her by telling her that passengers with a ticket were not allowed aboard the train!
For millions of Russians, corruption is a normal way of life.
If you don't want your son to be called up for military service, buy an army clerk and he will remove your son's name from the list or bribe a doctor to declare him unfit for any military activity.
You can enter any university for a certain price, regardless of your references and diplomas.
You can drive drunk, speed, and run red lights as long as Ben Franklin is there to bribe the police.
Alexander Menchikov, Peter the Great's minister, had understood the impossibility of winning the fight against corruption.
When the tsar Peter, disgusted by the corruption in Russia, decided to hang his corrupt officials, Menchikov replied to him: "Your Majesty, you risk losing all your subjects."
In the centuries that have passed since, the situation has worsened.
Eliminating corruption could well leave the State without citizens, but if the spread of corruption is not stopped, the citizens will soon be left without a State.
